          "libraryTitle": "Multiple Choice",
          "action": {
            "library": "H5P.MultiChoice 1.16",
            "params": {
              "question": "<p>A nurse accidentally administers a gluteal intramuscular injection into the lower inner quadrant. The patient develops foot drop and sensory loss over the sole. Which nerve has been injured?</p>",
              "answers": [
                {
                  "text": "<div>Superior gluteal nerve</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>The superior gluteal nerve exits above piriformis and supplies gluteus medius and minimus. Its injury would cause hip abductor weakness and Trendelenburg sign, not foot drop.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>Inferior gluteal nerve</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>The inferior gluteal nerve supplies gluteus maximus only. Its injury would weaken hip extension — it does not innervate any muscle below the knee.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>Sciatic nerve</div>",
                  "correct": true,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>Correct. The sciatic nerve (L4–S3) passes midway between the ischial tuberosity and the greater trochanter. Injection into the lower inner quadrant hits it directly, paralysing all muscles below the knee and causing sensory loss over the sole and dorsum of the foot.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>Pudendal nerve</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>The pudendal nerve also exits below piriformis but loops around the ischial spine into the perineum. It supplies perineal structures, not the foot.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                }
              ],
              "overallFeedback": [
                {
                  "from": 0,
                  "to": 50,
                  "feedback": "Review the structures exiting below piriformis. The sciatic nerve passes midway between the ischial tuberosity and greater trochanter — the lower inner quadrant lies right in its path."
                },
                {
                  "from": 51,
                  "to": 100,
                  "feedback": "Well done. The upper outer quadrant or, better still, the ventrogluteal site (Hochstetter's method over the greater trochanter) avoids the sciatic nerve entirely."
                }
              ],
              "behaviour": {
