          "action": {
            "library": "H5P.MultiChoice 1.16",
            "params": {
              "question": "<p>Why is the popliteal artery particularly vulnerable to injury in posterior dislocation of the knee?</p>",
              "answers": [
                {
                  "text": "<div>It is the most superficial structure in the popliteal fossa</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>The popliteal artery is the deepest structure, closest to the bone. The tibial nerve is most superficial, followed by the popliteal vein.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>It is tethered at both ends and lies deepest, against the bone</div>",
                  "correct": true,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>Correct. The popliteal artery lies deepest in the fossa, pressed against the popliteal surface of the femur. Because it is fixed above and below, posterior dislocation stretches and tears it. Without urgent repair, limb loss can follow within six hours.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>It passes through the roof of the popliteal fossa</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>The small saphenous vein and the posterior cutaneous nerve of the thigh pierce the roof. The popliteal artery lies deep in the fossa, against the floor.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>It runs along the medial border of biceps femoris</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>The common peroneal nerve runs along the medial border of biceps femoris. The popliteal artery lies centrally and deeply, against the posterior surface of the femur.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                }
              ],
              "overallFeedback": [
                {
                  "from": 0,
                  "to": 50,
                  "feedback": "In the popliteal fossa, structures are arranged superficial to deep: tibial nerve → popliteal vein → popliteal artery (closest to bone). The artery is tethered at both ends, making it vulnerable when the knee dislocates posteriorly."
                },
                {
                  "from": 51,
                  "to": 100,
                  "feedback": "Excellent. Remember the superficial-to-deep order: tibial nerve, popliteal vein, popliteal artery. The artery's fixed, deep position makes it the structure most at risk in posterior knee dislocation."
                }
              ],
